    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI2"/>, p. 267, n. <citedRange>545</citedRange>, fig. 108</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.317</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#maffre2007"/>, p. 170, n. <citedRange>15</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>030500</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#lazzarini1976"/>, p. 275, n. <citedRange>700</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Apollo"><name nymRef="#Ἀπόλλων">Ἀπόλλωνος</name></persName> <w>δεκάτα</w>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Dîme d'Apollon.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Apollo's tithe.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Decima di Apollo.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This complete inscription shows clearly one of the two formulations of the tithe: nominative of the word 'tithe' and genitive of the 
                god's name, who becomes the owner of the dedicated object. On the whole, this formulation is a sort of caption.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
